        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <h3>Configuring Organisation Schema on WordPress</h3>
          <p>
            Organisation schema at the site root is the single most important schema addition for most WordPress GEO projects.
            AI engines use it to resolve your brand as a distinct entity — assigning it a category, attributes, and relationships.
            Without it, your site is a collection of pages with no clear brand context.
          </p>
          <p>
            A complete Organisation schema for WordPress should include: <code>name</code>, <code>url</code>, <code>logo</code>
            (ImageObject with width, height, and caption), <code>description</code> (one clear sentence describing what the
            organisation does), <code>foundingDate</code>, <code>email</code>, <code>areaServed</code>, and a <code>sameAs</code>
            array containing links to Wikidata, Wikipedia (if applicable), LinkedIn, Companies House, and any industry-specific
            directories. Set this in Rank Math Pro under Titles &amp; Meta → Local SEO, or in Yoast's Knowledge Graph settings.
          </p>

          <h3>FAQPage Schema: Per-Post Implementation</h3>
          <p>
            FAQPage schema should be added to every WordPress post or page that contains a question-and-answer section. With
            Rank Math Pro, this is configured per-post in the Schema tab of the post editor. With Yoast, use the FAQ Gutenberg block,
            which auto-generates FAQPage schema from the block content. With WP Schema Pro, create a rule that automatically applies
            FAQPage schema to all posts in specified categories.
          </p>
          <p>
            The most common FAQPage error on WordPress is schema that references questions not present in the visible page content.
            AI engines cross-reference schema content against page text. Discrepancies reduce citation confidence.
            Every question in your FAQPage schema must be visible and readable on the published page.
          </p>
          <p>
            For full schema implementation guidance, see
            <a href="/schema-markup-ai/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">schema markup for AI</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="content-structure" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Content Structure for AI Citation on WordPress</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The most impactful GEO change you can make to a WordPress site is restructuring how posts and pages open.</strong>
          AI retrieval systems are biased towards content that begins with a clear, definitional statement — a sentence that directly
          and confidently answers the most likely query for that page. Most WordPress content buries this statement in the second or
          third paragraph, after an introductory hook. That structure works for human readers; it fails for AI extraction.
        </p>

        <h3>The GEO Content Template for WordPress Posts</h3>
        <p>
          Apply this structure to every pillar post and commercial landing page:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Opening definition</strong> — one sentence that states what the topic is, using the target keyword naturally.</li>
          <li><strong>Why it matters now</strong> — one to two sentences with a specific, verifiable claim about context or scale.</li>
          <li><strong>What the page covers</strong> — a brief scoped statement so AI engines know which sub-questions this page answers.</li>
          <li><strong>Body sections</strong> — each section opens with a bold declarative sentence. Use H2 and H3 headings that mirror question phrasings AI users are likely to ask.</li>
          <li><strong>Data or examples</strong> — at least one specific, sourced data point per major section.</li>
          <li><strong>FAQ section</strong> — five to eight Q&amp;A pairs, each self-contained, with FAQPage schema applied.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          This structure serves dual purposes: it improves AI citation rates by making the content easy to extract, and it
          improves traditional search performance through better semantic organisation and featured snippet eligibility.
        </p>

        <h3>Heading Hierarchy and AI Navigation</h3>
        <p>
          AI retrieval systems use heading structure to navigate long-form content and to identify which section answers a
          given query. A correct heading hierarchy on WordPress means: one H1 per page (the post title, set by your theme),
          H2 for major sections, H3 for subsections, and no skipped levels (H1 to H3 without an H2 in between).
          Many WordPress themes add a second H1 for the site name — audit your theme's template files and correct any
          duplicate H1 occurrences.
        </p>

        <h3>Tables as AI-Citable Content</h3>
        <p>
          Structured comparison tables are among the most frequently cited content formats in AI-generated responses to
          "best of" and "compare" queries. WordPress's Gutenberg editor produces clean HTML table markup that AI parsers
          handle correctly. Every comparison post — tool comparisons, approach comparisons, option breakdowns — should
          include at least one HTML table with descriptive column headers using <code>&lt;th scope="col"&gt;</code> attributes.
          Avoid creating tables as images or using table plugins that output complex nested div structures, as these
          reduce AI parsability.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <section id="technical-setup" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Technical Setup for WordPress GEO</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The technical foundation of WordPress GEO is ensuring AI crawlers can access, parse, and trust your content without obstruction.</strong>
          Three areas require explicit attention: crawler access configuration, page speed (which affects RAG retrieval reliability),
          and canonical URL consistency.
        </p>

        <h3>Core Web Vitals and AI Retrieval</h3>
        <p>
          Perplexity and similar RAG-based AI systems retrieve pages in real time when generating answers. Pages that load slowly,
          time out under crawler conditions, or produce JavaScript-rendered content that headless crawlers cannot execute will be
          less reliably retrieved. WordPress sites using page builders (Elementor, Divi, WPBakery) frequently suffer from
          large JavaScript payloads that degrade crawler performance. Ensure your critical content pages produce a meaningful
          HTML payload in the initial server response — do not rely entirely on client-side rendering for body content.
        </p>

        <h3>Canonical URL Consistency</h3>
        <p>
          WordPress frequently creates multiple URLs for the same content: paginated archives, tag pages, category pages, and
          author pages can all produce duplicate or near-duplicate content accessible at different URLs. Configure your schema
          plugin to output <code>mainEntityOfPage</code> canonical URLs on all Article schema, and ensure your canonical link
          elements match those URLs exactly. AI engines encountering multiple URLs for the same content may split citation
          credit between them or avoid citing either.
        </p>

        <h3>Site Speed Recommendations for GEO</h3>
        <p>
          For WordPress sites prioritising AI visibility, the most impactful performance improvements are: switching to a
          lightweight theme (Kadence, GeneratePress, or Blocksy) if on a builder-heavy theme, enabling full-page caching
          (WP Rocket, LiteSpeed Cache, or W3 Total Cache), serving images in WebP format, and hosting on a server with
          response times below 200ms. These changes reduce the probability of RAG crawlers timing out on your pages.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <section id="llms-txt-wordpress" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Deploying llms.txt on WordPress</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>WordPress is the most straightforward major CMS for llms.txt deployment because you have direct access to the document root.</strong>
          Unlike Shopify (which requires workarounds) or some managed hosting environments, a standard WordPress installation
          on shared or VPS hosting allows you to place a static file at the root level that is immediately accessible at
          <code>yourdomain.com/llms.txt</code>.
        </p>

        <h3>Method 1: Static File Upload (Recommended)</h3>
        <p>
          Upload your <code>llms.txt</code> file to the WordPress root directory — the same directory that contains
          <code>wp-config.php</code> and <code>wp-login.php</code> — using FTP, SFTP, or your hosting control panel's
          file manager (cPanel File Manager, Plesk, etc.). No .htaccess rules, no plugin configuration, and no WordPress
          code changes are needed. The file will be served as plain text by your web server automatically.
        </p>
        <p>
          After uploading, verify the file is accessible at <code>yourdomain.com/llms.txt</code> in a browser and confirm
          it returns <code>Content-Type: text/plain</code> in the response headers. Update the file manually whenever you
          add new high-authority content areas to the site.
        </p>

        <h3>Method 2: WordPress Rewrite Endpoint</h3>
        <p>
          For sites where direct file system access is restricted, or where the llms.txt content should be dynamically
          generated from WordPress post data, add a custom rewrite endpoint in your theme's <code>functions.php</code>
          or a site-specific plugin:
        </p>
        <pre class="mt-4 rounded-lg bg-geo-900 border border-geo-800 p-4 text-xs font-mono text-ink-200 overflow-x-auto"><code>add_action('init', function() &#123;
  add_rewrite_rule('^llms\.txt$', 'index.php?llms_txt=1', 'top');
&#125;);
add_filter('query_vars', fn($v) => array_merge($v, ['llms_txt']));
add_action('template_redirect', function() &#123;
  if (!get_query_var('llms_txt')) return;
  header('Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8');
  // Output your llms.txt content here
  exit;
&#125;);</code></pre>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Flush rewrite rules after adding this code by visiting Settings → Permalinks and saving.
        </p>

        <p>
          For full llms.txt content strategy and structure guidance, see the
          <a href="/llms-txt/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">complete llms.txt guide</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6 -->
      <section id="robots-txt-crawlers" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Robots.txt and AI Crawlers on WordPress</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>WordPress's robots.txt is one of the most common sources of accidental AI visibility suppression.</strong>
          The file can be generated dynamically by WordPress core (accessible at <code>/robots.txt</code> without a physical file),
          overridden by a static file in the document root, or modified by SEO plugins — creating multiple potential sources of
          conflicting rules.
        </p>

        <h3>Auditing Your WordPress Robots.txt</h3>
        <p>
          Visit <code>yourdomain.com/robots.txt</code> in a browser and examine every Disallow rule. Check for any of the
          following AI crawler user agent strings in Disallow directives:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>GPTBot</code> — OpenAI's crawler for ChatGPT training and retrieval</li>
          <li><code>ClaudeBot</code> — Anthropic's crawler</li>
          <li><code>PerplexityBot</code> — Perplexity's retrieval crawler</li>
          <li><code>Google-Extended</code> — Google's AI training crawler (separate from Googlebot)</li>
          <li><code>CCBot</code> — Common Crawl, a primary source for LLM training data</li>
          <li><code>anthropic-ai</code> — alternative Anthropic crawler identifier</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          If any of these appear with Disallow rules covering paths you want AI-crawled, remove those rules. If you are using
          Yoast SEO or Rank Math, check their respective robots.txt configuration sections — both plugins allow you to add
          custom directives that may have been set to block AI bots during earlier plugin updates.
        </p>

        <h3>WordPress Robots.txt Priority Order</h3>
        <p>
          WordPress resolves robots.txt in this priority order: (1) a physical <code>robots.txt</code> file in the document
          root overrides everything; (2) if no physical file exists, WordPress generates one dynamically, which SEO plugins
          can then filter via the <code>robots_txt</code> hook. To ensure full control, use a physical static file and
          configure it to explicitly allow the AI crawlers you want to permit.
        </p>
      </section>

